i# Very Important System Configuration		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- First, **MAKE SURE** that you enabled Linux's packet forwarding, or		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  `ip_forwarding`.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - There is no absolute "client" in DN42. Everyone's server is a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    router for others and needs to forward packets. The steps are:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    ```bash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    echo "net.ipv4.ip_forward=1" >> /etc/sysctl.conf		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    echo "net.ipv6.conf.default.forwarding=1" >> /etc/sysctl.conf		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    echo "net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding=1" >> /etc/sysctl.conf		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    sysctl -p		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    ```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - By the way, if you configured a firewall like `iptables`, check		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    the configuration and make sure they don't block packet		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    forwarding.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Then, **MAKE SURE** to disable Linux `rp_filter`'s strict mode:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ```bash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  echo "net.ipv4.conf.default.rp_filter=0" >> /etc/sysctl.conf		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  echo "net.ipv4.conf.all.rp_filter=0" >> /etc/sysctl.conf		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  sysctl -p		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - `rp_filter` is a network security mechanism of the Linux kernel.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    It checks the packet's source address and the source network		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    interface:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - If set to 0 (disabled), allow all packets.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - Some packets that cannot be replied to correctly (no entries		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        in the routing table) will be processed by userspace		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        applications, possibly consuming extra resources.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - But the overhead should be tiny, so setting to 0 is no issue		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        here.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - If set to 1 (strict), if the packet doesn't come from the "best"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      network interface (or in other words, your machine will reply to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      the packet on a different network interface), the packet will be		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      **dropped**.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - Having different network interfaces for source and reply is		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        **very common** in DN42, so **MAKE SURE** you don't set		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        `rp_filter` to 1!		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - If set to 2 (relaxed), **in theory**, Linux will only drop		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      packets that don't have a source address in the routing table,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      which means it doesn't know how to properly reply to them.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - However, theory is just theory. In newer versions (5.0+) of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        the kernel, still, a lot of normal packets with correct source		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        addresses are dropped. Therefore, don't use this mode, please		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        stick to 0 instead.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Then, **MAKE SURE** to turn off any tool that helps you configure		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  `iptables` easily, such as UFW.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - These easy tools may use some assumptions that are suitable for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    personal users but are not suitable for DN42, such as using		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    conntrack.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Conntrack filters packets from links it hasn't seen before,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      effectively doing strict `rp_filter`.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - I personally recommend you to configure iptable manually.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Choose Tunnel Software		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAlmost every peering in DN42 is established on tunneling software (or		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iVPN) since:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- DN42 nodes are spread across the world, and tunneling provides basic		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  encryption and protection;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
