i## Building Internal Network		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIf you have multiple servers joining DN42, you need to configure your		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iinternal network first. Your network needs to satisfy the following		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
irequirements to work normally:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. Proper communication (or pingable) between any two servers		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - Routers outside your AS are only responsible for sending the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     packet to your own AS, and the packet may enter from any node.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     Your own node needs to forward the packet to the correct node.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - You may use these schemes:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     1. A full-mesh VPN with Tinc, ZeroTier One, etc., so any two		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        servers can talk directly.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     2. $\frac{n (n-1)}{2}$ point-to-point tunnels with OpenVPN,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        WireGuard, etc., so any two servers can talk directly.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     3. **(Relatively Dangerous)** Use OpenVPN, WireGuard, etc., to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        create less than $\frac{n (n-1)}{2}$ tunnels, but make sure		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        there is a path between any two servers (intermediate nodes		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        allowed). Then use Babel, OSPF, RIP, etc., to find the path in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        your own network.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     - In this scheme, it's easy to make mistakes and **cause		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i       catastrophic failures**.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i       - Some real examples are available at		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
         		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
1How to Kill the DN42 Network	/en/article/modify-website/how-to-kill-the-dn42-network.lantian/	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i.i     - Routing protocols, including Babel, OSPF, RIP, etc., can		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i       automatically detect the topology of your whole network and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i       configure the routes.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     - But Babel, OSPF, RIP are only supposed to handle your internal		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i       routing, and **shouldn't be used to forward routes received		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i       externally from BGP!**		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i       - When BGP routing information is forwarded by Babel, OSPF,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i         RIP, information such as source, route length, and BGP		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i         communities are all lost.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i       - Therefore, your other nodes will think that the route **comes		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i         from your own network** and broadcast the route to others		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i         with your AS as the source.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i       - In short: you will **hijack the whole DN42**.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     - Babel, OSPF, RIP should be strictly restricted to your own IP		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i       range. **External routing must be handled by BGP**.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     - If you have questions, seek help at		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i       [the unofficial Telegram group](https://t.me/Dn42Chat).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. BGP configuration must satisfy one of:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   1. One BGP session between each of your two servers.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - BGP has a feature that, within one AS, a BGP node will only		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        broadcast routes that it **received externally** and **won't		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        forward** routes it received from other internal nodes in the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        AS. It is to prevent any occurrence of route loops. Therefore,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        each server needs to establish BGP sessions with all other		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        servers, so it can obtain a complete routing table.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - If you have a lot of servers, you will have fun configuring		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        each server by hand. You may consider writing a script or		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        using any plan below.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   2. Configure one server as a `BGP Route Reflector` and establish		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      BGP sessions with all other servers.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - Route Reflector will manage and broadcast all routing		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        information within the AS.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - Compared to the last scheme, you will need to do substantially		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        less configuration, but if the Route Reflector is down, your		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        whole network is dead.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - Note that I haven't tried this configuration and cannot		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        provide any technical help.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - If you have questions, seek help at		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        [the unofficial Telegram group](https://t.me/Dn42Chat), where		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        some users use this scheme.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   3. Configure a different private ASN at each node, and configure		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      BGP Confederation.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - ASN should be in the private ASN range 4200000000 -		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        4294967294, but not 4242420000 - 4242429999 since it may		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        overlap with other DN42 users.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - With Confederation, multiple servers team together and appear		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        as one AS when observed externally.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - See		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
        		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
1Bird BGP Confederation: Configuration and Emulation	/en/article/modify-website/bird-confederation.lantian	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i.i      - If you have questions, seek help at		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        [the unofficial Telegram group](https://t.me/Dn42Chat), where		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        some other users also use this scheme.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
